Over the past two years, I have found my caseload get bigger, while the time I am able to offer my patients is forcibly reduced. I’m a psychotherapist in Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) in London. We are underfunded, understaffed, and under-resourced, and as with many trusts, retention of staff is difficult with a record number of workers leaving the profession entirely, including relatively newly trained clinicians. In fact, a record number of 400 workers a week have been leaving the NHS for reasons of burnout and PTSD. And now, despite having worked in a crumbling health care system – where waiting lists are now the longest they have ever been since records began – over the course of a pandemic, NHS staff are being insulted with a 3% pay rise offer. This comes at a time of the highest cost of living crisis for a generation and inflation hitting 5.5%. The proposed pay rise will, once again, see us left with a real-terms pay cut not far from the insulting 1% pay rise we were offered last year, neither of which make up for the slashes to staff pay due to public sector austerity cuts. After years of underfunding and closures to services by the Government, more patients are being turned away than ever, and the NHS is unrecognisable. Across the board, we are physically and psychologically drained and many of our colleagues continue to leave the workforce for better conditions and lighter workloads elsewhere. Recent comments from the likes of Kirstie Allsopp suggesting working people’s wages would last longer if we sacrificed expenses like our morning coffees are careless, infuriating and trivialise the everyday sacrifices we make. In the NHS, some of us are employed on insecure contracts due to a lack of funding available for recruitment. For these workers, late agency payments can result in the inability to pay bills on time and avoid overdraft fees. A 3% pay rise not only fails to show appreciation for an overstretched workforce, but also seems to ignore the fact that the NHS is at its greatest threat of collapse due to the lack of staff available. {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"VideoObject","name":"Metro.co.uk","duration":"T1M","thumbnailUrl":"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2022/01/17/08/53015159-0-image-a-31_1642408271494.jpg","uploadDate":"2022-01-17T08:30:28+0000","description":"Feelings like anxiety and depression can affect us all and the NHS is here to help.","contentUrl":"https://videos.metro.co.uk/video/met/2022/01/17/2218644681484777253/480x270_MP4_2218644681484777253.mp4","height":270,"width":480}  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web
